#MEM id=rules source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Technical/mia/skills/design-and-build/vercel-react-best-practices/rules/async-cheap-condition-before-await.md
M|rules|title: Check Cheap Conditions Before Async Flags
M|rules|impact: HIGH
M|rules|impactDescription: avoids unnecessary async work when a synchronous guard already fails
M|rules|tags: async, await, feature-flags, short-circuit, conditional
M|rules|When a branch uses `await` for a flag or remote value and also requires a **cheap synchronous** condition (local props, request metadata, already-loaded state), evaluate the cheap condition **first**.
M|rules|This is a specialization of [Defer Await Until Needed](./async-defer-await.md) for `flag && cheapCondition` style checks.
M|rules|**Incorrect:**
M|rules|```typescript
M|rules|const someFlag = await getFlag()
M|rules|if (someFlag && someCondition) {
M|rules|// ...
M|rules|}
M|rules|```
M|rules|**Correct:**
M|rules|```typescript
M|rules|if (someCondition) {
M|rules|const someFlag = await getFlag()
M|rules|if (someFlag) {
M|rules|// ...
M|rules|}
M|rules|}
M|rules|```
M|rules|This matters when `getFlag` hits the network, a feature-flag service, or `React.cache` / DB work: skipping it when `someCondition` is false removes that cost on the cold path.
M|rules|Keep the original order if `someCondition` is expensive, depends on the flag, or you must run side effects in a fixed order.